      "id": 1,
      "text": "Narrowsburg sits on the eastern shore of the Delaware River, right on the New York–Pennsylvania border.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        11
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narrowsburg%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "The town lies between the Catskill and Pocono Mountains, offering a gateway to two iconic ranges.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        12
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narrowsburg%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "Three historic gems—Arlington Hotel, Kirk House, and Narrowsburg Methodist Church—are listed on the National Register of Historic Places.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narrowsburg%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "Before becoming Narrowsburg, the community was known as Homans Eddy, named for early settler Benjamin Homan.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        3
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Narrowsburg%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Drivers will find Narrowsburg at the crossroads of New York Routes 52 and 97, a classic junction of the region.",
